http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20070531.wblacktor31/BNStory/ConradBlack/home&cid reportonbusiness.com: Prosecutors drop laundering charge against Black Letters to the Editor Prosecutors drop laundering charge against Black Defence lawyers to begin their cases From Thursday's Globe and Mail May 31, 2007 at 3:56 AM EDT &#151; Prosecutors ended their case against Conrad Black yesterday by withdrawing one criminal charge and showing the jury more examples of Lord Black's lavish lifestyle and colourful language. &#34;At this time, the government rests,&#34; lead prosecutor Eric Sussman told the court in mid-afternoon, ending more than two months of witness testimony, legal arguments and document presentation, all aimed at persuading jurors that Lord Black should go to prison. Just before that, Mr. Sussman withdrew a money-laundering charge against Lord Black. The charge was among the most serious Lord Black faced and it had been added to the indictment with great fanfare by prosecutors, along with racketeering, in December of 2005. The charge related to agreements struck when Hollinger International Inc. sold most of its Canadian newspapers to CanWest Global Communications Corp. in 2000 for $3.2-billion. In that transaction, $80-million was set aside to cover payments under non-competition agreements CanWest signed with Lord Black and three other Hollinger executives. Lord Black and David Radler, who pleaded guilty, each received about $18-million. Former National Post editor to testify Black trial sees video of box removal Assistant could be defence's first witness Conrad Black trial loses another juror Black trial nearing end 'Dear Donald, Could I ask a rather esoteric favor? &hellip;' How Black built his empire');"> How Black built his empire When Lord Black and the others were charged, prosecutors alleged all of the non-competition payments should have gone to Hollinger. Shortly after the trial began, prosecutors conceded that the payments to Lord Black and Mr. Radler were legal but they said Lord Black still faced charges for arranging non-competes for defendants Peter Atkinson and John Boultbee. The money-laundering charge, which relates to the wiring of Lord Black's non-compete funds, only applied to Lord Black and it related directly to the CanWest deal. Mr. Sussman and lawyers for Lord Black declined to comment. Lord Black still faces several charges of fraud, racketeering and tax evasion stemming from non-competition agreements in other Hollinger deals. Prosecutors ended their case yesterday the way they began it, by showing the jury some of Lord Black's e-mails. In an e-mail sent to a Hollinger director, Lord Black referred to a shareholder revolt over the non-competition payments as &#34;regrettable nonsense.&#34; A later e-mail to Mr. Atkinson called the company a &#34;vehicle for extracting money as in the non competes.&#34; Prosecutors also gave the jury a glimpse into Lord Black's personal life yesterday by showing some of the items he stuffed into 13 boxes that he carted out of his Toronto office on May 20, 2005. Prosecutors have alleged Lord Black was obstructing justice by removing the boxes, but Lord Black has insisted he was only taking personal items. He returned the boxes within days. Prosecutor Jeffrey Cramer showed the jury several bank statements found in the boxes. The statement indicated that Lord Black purchased a $2.6-million, 26-carat diamond ring from Graff Diamond Ltd. The bank records also showed Lord Black spent $116,000 at Yves St. Laurent, $150,000 at a book dealer, and $101,000 at Fendi. In court filings, prosecutors have alleged Lord Black used Hollinger money to pay for many personal expenses. The expenses and e-mails will likely figure prominently when prosecutors make their closing arguments. For weeks, prosecutors have tried to use these sorts of documents to illustrate Lord Black's disdain for shareholders and his sense of entitlement. &#34;Mr. Black believes this is his company and he is above the shareholders,&#34; Mr. Sussman said yesterday during a hearing without the jury present. Much of the prosecution case also rests on whether the jury finds their witnesses credible. Many of the high-profile prosecution witnesses, such as former Illinois governor James Thompson, former ambassador Richard Burt and economist Marie-Jos&#233;e Kravis, faced rough cross-examinations that dented their credibility. All three acknowledged they did not read key company documents. Mr. Radler also faced gruelling questioning about past lies and whether he reached a plea agreement to save himself. Prosecutors will likely try to draw the jury back to some of their first witnesses, who faced fewer challenges. Those witnesses included several men who bought newspapers from Hollinger and who testified that they did not want non-competition agreements with Lord Black and the others. One of the buyers, Michael Reed, told the jury that he refused to wire payments to Lord Black and the others. Defence lawyers will begin presenting their cases today. They are expected to take about two weeks in total and there is little indication that Lord Black or any of the others will testify. Comments are closed for this story | Send a letter to the editor Add PAUL WALDIE to my e-mail alerts Top Stories by Section CIBC profit rises sharply, but shares slip Governments, police share Ipperwash blame, probe says Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Hewitt rallies to reach third round A robust hit that never falters Alleged top world spammer arrested in Seattle A 40-year wait for wedded bliss Tories take another swipe at Dion Canadian soldier among seven killed in Afghan helicopter crash Senators slide into 2-0 hole Has big business turned organics into 'yuppy chow'? Submit post to digg.com Seed this post at Newsvine Technorati links to this post A tag is a keyword or descriptive term supplied by our editorial staff used to associate related articl