ete payments from Hollinger International during the sale of newspaper assets. All have pleaded not guilty. The decision provided a bright spot for the defence before the jury arrived and prosecutors introduced a stack of documents found inside the 13 boxes that Black was videotaped removing from Hollinger Inc.â€™s office in Toronto into evidence. The boxes included receipts for purchases Black had made at a number of luxury stores, among them more than $116,000 US at Yves St. Laurent; $101,550 US at Fendi and $2.62 million US at Graff Diamonds Limited. Prosecutor Jeffrey Cramer also flashed bank statements showing a deposit made to Black for $4.3 million US from American Publishing Company on April 9, 2001, and travel documents from Tekura Tahiti Travel related to Blackâ€™s trip to Bora Bora. An original copy of a contract signed by Black was also shown to the jury. The contents of the battered office boxes, which have been sitting in front of the jurors on a trolley in the courtroom for days, had largely remained a mystery to them until Wednesday. The jury also saw an e-mail that Black sent to co-defendant Peter Atkinson on Jan. 17, 2003, referring to a public company as a â€œvehicle for extracting money, as in the non-competes.â€ After presenting the jury with the flurry of documents, Sussman announced, â€œAt this time, the prosecution rests.â€ After jurors filed out of the courtroom, Black and his wife, Barbara Amiel, left the room holding hands. The press baron had a faint smile on his lips. Black is facing an additional charge of obstruction of justice, which is directly linked to the removal of the boxes. After the jurors had left for the day, Marc Martin, a defence lawyer for Black, applied to St. Eve to have all of the charges against the press baron dismissed. He took particular exception with the obstruction of justice charge, arguing that were it not for an Ontario court order that prevented the removal of documents from Hollinger Inc. in May 20005, the charge would have no basis. â€œWe donâ€™t know what Mr. Blackâ€™s intention was,â€ Martin argued, pointing out that the press baron had been ordered to vacate the office by the end of the month. Sussman argued the charge is also directly relevant to investigations by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and a grand jury, as well as the federal court proceedings in Chicago. Lawyers for Blackâ€™s co-defendants also applied to have various charges against their clients dismissed. The defence will begin presenting its case today. The first witness expected to be called is call Joan Maida, Blackâ€™s personal assistant in Toronto, as its first witness on Thursday. Ken Whyte, the editor of Macleanâ€™s magazine, who has selected by Black to launch the National Post, will also take the stand. Defence attorneys have indicated their case will not be lengthy and will likely wrap up in the second week of June. Edward Greenspan, a Canadian lawyer representing Black, told St. Eve that he had intended to call a parole lawyer from British Columbia to explain the sentence that David Radler, Blackâ€™s former lieutenant in Canada, could be expected to serve in Canada after signing his so-called â€œsweetheart dealâ€ with prosecutors in exchange for his testimony and a lenient 29-month sentence. But Greenspan said that when he called the provinceâ€™s leading lawyer, who he did not name, he was informed the lawyer was already working for Radler. That lawyer, however, could still end up testifying about his relationship with Radler at the criminal trial in Chicago. Radler previously testified that he was unaware of that he could spend as little as six months in prison under Canadian laws. He has indicated he would like to serve his sentence in British Columbia, near his home. Copyright & Permission Rules Broadcasters of the Future Awards This site is part of the var expDays = 365; var exp = new Date(); exp.setTime(exp.getTime() + (expDays*24*60*60*1000)); var cookiename = GetCookie(