http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-1&fd=R&url=http://biznes.onet.pl/5,1545598,wiadomosci.html&cid=1116840694&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ DJ US 1Q GDP Revised To +0.6% Rate From +1.3% - DowJonesNewswires - Onet.pl Biznes - 31.05.2007 DJ US 1Q GDP Revised To +0.6% Rate From +1.3% (DowJonesNewswires, tm/31.05.2007, godz. 14:30) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--The U.S. economy slowed to a crawl in early 2007, according to data Thursday by the government, which adjusted the growth rate to less than half its initial estimate due to shrinking business inventories and stronger imports. =============================================================== GDP Preliminary Report ! Consensus: ! 1Q 1Q 4Q ! +0.8% ! Overall GDP Growth +0.6% +1.3% +2.5% ! Actual: ! PCE Price Index +3.3% +3.4% -1.0% ! +0.6% ! =============================================================== Gross domestic product rose at a seasonally adjusted 0.6% annual rate January through March, the Commerce Department said in a new, revised estimate of first-quarter GDP. It was the weakest performance since a 0.2% increase in fourth-quarter 2002 GDP. Originally, the government had estimated first-quarter 2007 GDP rose 1.3%. Fourth-quarter 2006 GDP climbed 2.5%. Corporate profits got a bit stronger in the first three months of 2007. Profits after taxes grew by 1.0% to $1.184 trillion in the first quarter, after rising by 0.8% in the fourth quarter. Year over year, profits increased 6.4%. Price inflation gauges were barely touched in the government's revisions to the economic data. The economy's engine, consumer spending, was revised higher, but bigger imports and a drawdown by businesses in inventories led to a sharp downward revision to GDP, a measure of all goods and services produced in the economy. Wall Street was a little surprised by the size of the adjustment; the median estimate of 24 economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires was a 0.8% increase. The report showed businesses decreased inventories in the first quarter, a decline of $4.5 billion. Originally, Commerce estimated a $14.8 billion increase. Companies had elevated stocks $22.4 billion in the fourth quarter. The drawdown of goods in the first quarter reduced GDP during that period by 0.98 percentage point. In its original report on first-quarter GDP, Commerce said inventories subtracted 0.30 percentage point from growth. Trade took a bigger bite out of the economy than first estimated - because U.S. imports were stronger, rising 5.7% instead of the originally reported 2.3%. Exports were revised higher, falling 0.6% instead of 1.2%. Trade cut GDP by 1.00 percentage points in the first quarter. Originally, trade was seen reducing GDP by 0.52 percentage point. Businesses increased spending more than previously thought. Outlays rose by 2.9% January through March, an advance bigger than the originally estimated 2.0% increase. Business spending fell 3.1% in the fourth quarter. First-quarter investment in structures increased 5.1%. Equipment and software rose 2.0%. First-quarter spending by consumers advanced 4.4%, up from a previously reported 3.8% increase and above the fourth quarter's 4.2% climb. Consumer spending accounts for about 70% of economic activity. It contributed 3.01 percentage points to GDP in the first quarter; the original estimate was a contribution of 2.66 percentage points. Purchases of durable goods surged 8.8% in January through March, above the previously reported 7.3% increase and double the rate of 4.4% in the fourth quarter. Durable goods are expensive items designed to last at least three years, such as refrigerators. First-quarter non-durables spending rose by 3.5%. Services spending went 4.0% higher. Residential fixed investment, which includes spending on housing, plunged by 15.4% in the first quarter, a smaller drop than the originally estimated 17.0%. Fourth-quarter spending fell by 19.8%. Real final sales of domestic product, which is GDP less the change in private inventories, climbed an unrevised 1.6%. Fourth-quarter sales rose 3.7%. Federal government spending decreased by 3.9%, revised down from an initially estimated 3.0% decline. Fourth-quarter spending rose 4.6%. State and local government outlays rose 3.9%. Revisions to inflation gauges within the report were generally left alone. The government's price index for personal consumption increased 3.3%, below the previously estimated 3.4% advance but above the fourth quarter's 1.0% decrease. The PCE price gauge excluding food and energy rose an unrevised 2.2%, above the fourth quarter's 1.8% increase. The price index for gross domestic purchases, which measures prices paid by U.S. residents, went up an unchanged 3.6%, which was above the fourth quarter's 0.2% increase. The chain-weighted GDP rose an unrevised 4.0%, above the fourth quarter's 1.7% increase. Copyright C2003, Dow Jones and Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved Nie ma jeszcze ¿adnych komentarzy Notowania opó¼nione o 15 min. Copyright 1996 - 2007 Grupa Onet.pl SA
http://online.wsj.com/article/SB118059273151919810.html%3Fmod%3Dgooglenews_wsj&cid Free Article - WSJ.com Free Dow Jones Sites 8:56 a.m. EDT Thursday, May 31, 2007 Set My Home Page FROM THE WALL STREET Americans Get Too Little Sleep Americans say they yearn for more sleep. But when it comes to actually getting it, most make excuses and delay sleep time. Web Sites Help Users Write Their Life Stories Sarmad Ali tests two Web sites that help people to write accounts of their life stories or family histories. But the results can be disappointing, especially for those who opt for the least expensive services. Polo's High-Stakes Balancing Act Ralph Lauren's ability to juggle so many brands in so many price categories and retail channels without tainting his luxury image is increasingly a model the rest of the fashion industry is seeking to emulate. Credit Suisse and Quattrone: Dueling Sequels Credit Suisse's tech-banking group is attempting a comeback at the same time that Frank Quattrone, who left under a cloud in 2003, is seeking to mount his own. MORE FROM TODAY'S JOURNAL Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards Stocks Rise Amid Data, Deals News Gates, Jobs Trade Compliments White House Unveils New Climate Strategy U.S. GDP Growth Slows to 0.6% The Shape of Computers to Come? Four Are Charged in Tax-Shelter Case 'Subprime' Aftermath: Losing the Family Home Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards Chances of Fed Rate Cut Diminish U.S. Firms' Use of Chemical Could Change China Debate HONG KONG -- The use of a potentially dangerous chemical as an animal feed additive by a pair of U.S. companies could shift the terms of a debate now playing out over China's regulation of its food production and exports. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration Wednesday said it has alerted manufacturers of feed for livestock, fish and shrimp to a voluntary recall of products made by Tembec BTLSR Inc. of Toledo, Ohio. The FDA said Tembec had added melamine, an agent used in plastics and fire retardants but unfit for use in food, to animal feed agents to improve the product's texture. The FDA said Tembec is a contract manufacturer for another company, Uniscope Inc. of Johnstown, Colo. The FDA said that small amounts of melamine detected in the feed products suggest that the "consumption of pork, chicken, domestic fish and eggs from animals inadvertently fed animal feed contaminated with melamine and its analogues is very unlikely to pose a human health risk." China Refuses Shipment of Evian But the agency said the products made by Tembec and Uniscope also reportedly contained "a urea formaldehyde resin-type ingredient," a raw ingredient used to make the binding agent in these products. The FDA says it is investigating that as well. The findings are likely to have a significant impact because in recent months world-wide alarm over the appearance of melamine in pet food and animal feed has centered on China. Beijing has borne the brunt of global criticism over laxity in supervising its food producers. In late March, the FDA identified a small Chinese manufacturer in Jiangsu province as the source of melamine in wheat flour shipped to the U.S. The chemical was detected in pet food ingredients and linked to a number of deaths in cats and dogs in the U.S., leading to a massive product recall. The FDA yesterday added that "the companies have confirmed that Tembec added melamine as part of the formulation of the products to improve the binding properties of pelleted feed. Melamine is not approved as an additive" for any food, including animal feed. The companies have stopped adding melamine to their products, the FDA said. Tembec BTLSR is a subsidiary of Tembec Inc., a forest products company based in Montreal, Canada, which manufacturers newsprint and chemicals, among other products. Tembec Inc., whose shares are listed on the Toronto stock exchange, reported annual sales of 3.3 billion Canadian dollars in 2006 and a net loss of C$304 million for 2005 and 2006. The company employs around 9,000 people. In its 2006 annual report, Tembec Inc. said that one of its manufacturing facilities located in Toledo, Ohio, manufactures melamine. A man who answered the phone at the office of Tembec BTLSR declined to comment on the FDA report, referring questions to John Valley, an official of the company. A message left for Mr. Valley late Wednesday night in Ohio wasn't immediately returned. Messages left late Wednesday night for officials in the public affairs division of Tembec Inc. also weren't immediately returned. There was no answer at Uniscope's office in Colorado late Wednesday night.
