http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-3&fd=R&url=http://australianit.news.com.au/articles/0,7204,21824765%255E15306,00.html&cid=1116813923&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ IBM cuts another 1500 jobs | Australian IT May 31, 2007 02:53pm AEST IBM cuts another 1500 jobs Brian Bergstein in Boston | IBM has laid off 1570 US workers as part of an ongoing overhaul of operations in its giant technology services unit. The company carried out a similar level of job cuts at the beginning of the month, for a total of 3023 in this quarter and 3720 for the year, IBM spokesman Edward Barbini said. The cuts amount to roughly 1 per cent of the company's workforce, which totalled 355,000 people at the beginning of the year. But these small numbers reflect a big project inside IBM to transform its business. Services is IBM's biggest division by revenue, but the advent of lower-cost competition overseas has forced IBM to work harder to improve the unit's profit margins. In the first quarter, pre-tax income for IBM's tech services fell 19 per cent, even as revenue rose 7 per cent. Wednesday's job cuts were largely part of the company's response. Although IBM did not disclose where the layoffs were being made, the company had blamed the first-quarter profit shortfall on problems in its US outsourcing business. IBM executives said they expected no more layoffs this quarter. More cuts may follow later in the year. IBM's services overhaul not only involves cheaper labour - IBM's work force in India rose from 9000 in 2003 to 52,000 last year - but also a quest to use less labour, by rethinking or automating the way that services contracts are carried out. Last year, IBM adopted a business-retooling system known as Lean to find such opportunities. Robert Moffat, the IBM executive overseeing Lean, acknowledged it would reduce the need for some services labour, but contended that it would also create new work for the company because customers would be getting more for their money. Even as it has laid off 3700 people this year, IBM has hired 19,000 others. Mr Barbini would not provide a geographic breakdown. Email To A Friend Email To A Friend Information provided on this page will not be used for any other purpose than to notify the recipient of the article you have chosen. From here you can use the Social Web links to save IBM cuts another 1500 jobs to a social bookmarking site. Microsoft's new PC surfaces A million say Do Not Call ACCC Singapore's lapdog - Telstra Google takes big step offline Alleged 'spam king' arrested TiVo posts maiden profit Inline video player has not loaded - you can still go directly to the video player Also in Australian IT Alleged 'spam king' arrested A 27-year-old man described as one of the world's most prolific spammers has been arrested in the US. Google takes big step offline Top speed for $50 HP opens Defence account HEWLETT-PACKARD Australia has stitched up a $10.4 million computer supply contract with the Department of Defence. Path to the top Open source lizard stands guard FSX Service Pack 1 MICROSOFT has achieved a first with the release of a service pack for its Flight Simulator game. Entertainment on the go Welcome to our new website OVER the past few months a team of designers and programmers has been busy renovating AustralianIT. United vision for growth decade Also in the Australian Howard warms to greenhouse gas targets THE Coalition has signalled its willingness to accept a long-term target for cutting greenhouse gases as John Howard readies today ... PM ridicules Labor emissions plan APEC climate pact up to Australia, says Arroyo BHP appoints new chief executive BHP Billiton has appointed Marius Kloppers as its new chief executive to succeed Chip Goodyear when he retires in October. ACCC a lapdog, says Telstra Morgan Stanley makes $6.6bn offer for Investa Seven news chief to spend weekends in jail THE Seven Network's head of news and current affairs, Peter Meakin, has been sentenced to at least 14 months pe