http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-4&fd=R&url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-thu_networkmay31,0,7660990.story%3Fcoll%3Dchi-business-hed&cid=1116814102&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ CBS taps into social networking market | Chicago Tribune A $100 million mystery Red wolf pups unveiled at Lincoln Park Zoo Billboard called racy, wrong A most hollow oratory on Memorial Day 2nd builder eyes Evanston sky CBS taps into social networking market Broadcaster plans to expand Last.fm tool to variety of content Published May 31, 2007 Taking a page from rival broadcaster News Corp., CBS Corp. bought a social networking Web site on Wednesday. While CBS hopes its $280 million purchase of London-based Last.fm is as successful as the Fox network's ownership of MySpace.com, the goals are different. "We're going to take their core kernel of DNA and see if we can apply it around sports, news and entertainment," among other types of content, said Quincy Smith, president of CBS Interactive. Last.fm is a Web site for music fans that asks users to name their favorite artists and then creates for them a customized radio stream featuring similar tunes. It's called a preference engine, and CBS wants to apply that technology across the various types of content it produces and perhaps tap into a vast library of existing content. "It's not just music that can be streamed," said Martin Stiksel, one of three Last.fm co-founders who will remain with the company. "The scope and vision was always there to expand it out." In 2005, News Corp. bought MySpace, which now has about 56 million unique monthly visitors. Users have profile pages listing their favorite bands, movies and other interests. But the site cannot generate a recommendation for a new band, for instance, like Last.fm. "We wanted to replicate the word-of-mouth model," Stiksel said earlier this year of Last.fm, which began in 2003. "You have a network of friends that plays music you like. You share their interests, and that's essentially what Last.fm does." Stiksel said Wednesday that the company has registered the domain name Last.tv, and Smith confirmed it's something CBS will likely be using in the future. Smith is attracted to Last.fm because it taps into "the wisdom of crowds," a notion that is becoming increasingly influential across the Web. He also likes the site's audience, which Last.fm officially says reaches 15 million users a month worldwide. "It's probably closer to 20 million," Smith said, with only 4.5 million of those users from the U.S. But that taps into another issue for CBS: growing an international audience. "Ninety percent of our revenue is U.S. based," Smith said. "We needed a beachhead &#091;abroad&#093;." That U.S. audience could grow rapidly, however, as Last.fm on Thursday will introduce a new application, or widget, for Facebook.com users to download to their profile pages. It will allow users of Facebook, a social site similar to MySpace, to create personalized music streams their friends can also hear. David Card, an analyst for Jupiter Research, said the deal was a smart one for CBS. "Last.fm is a good product and it has a robust community," he said. "It has one of the few recommendation engines that taps into what I listen to and have" stored on my computer. Amazon.com also has a recommendation engine, he points out, "but that's only based on items I've purchased," not on what the user already owns. Stiksel said the Last.fm technology gives people "control of their entertainment." "We have, with our concept, a way for people to revolutionize how they use media, whether its music, TV or movies." Meanwhile, News Corp.'s Fox Interactive Media unit, which runs MySpace, announced two separate deals to buy sites Photobucket.com and Flektor.com. Photobucket is an application that links personal photos and videos to Web sites, including MySpace, and Flektor lets users edit audio and video content and embed the finished product on a Web site or blog. Financial terms were not disclosed, but sources cited by The Associated Press said Fox was paying about $300 million for Photobucket, about half of the $580 million News Corp. paid for MySpace. ---------- ebenderoff@tribune.com Chicago Bears Super Bowl coverage Wonders of the world 10 for the road Send a news tip What's in it for you? The day's top stories e-mailed to you each weekday. Exclusive access to Tribune experts for help with homework or research A free archive search of a year's worth of Chicago Tribune stories. Advice for making the most of a special night out. This month's featured offers include: Subscriber Advantage members can enjoy special offers such as save $30 off a pair of Camelot tickets with Michael York receive FREE Child Admission to the Nature Museum and , courtesy of Chicago Tribune Subscriber Advantage.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/67784.html&cid=1116824071&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ eBay in $75 mln buy of search site StumbleUpon has acquired Web surfing recommendation site StumbleUpon for $75 million in cash, matching the highest value reported as under discussion weeks ago."> eBay in $75 mln buy of search site StumbleUpon has acquired Web surfing recommendation site StumbleUpon for $75 million in cash, matching the highest value reported as under discussion weeks ago." align="left"> Wed, 30 May 2007 21:20:01GMT US Business News | SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) - Web auction leader eBay Inc. has acquired Web surfing recommendation site StumbleUpon for $75 million in cash, matching the highest value reported as under discussion weeks ago. StumbleUpon Inc. is an online review site that recommends Web pages within sites such as Flickr, MySpace or YouTube, based on "thumbs up" or "thumbs down" votes from other Web users with shared interests. It counts 2.3 million users and is growing at 150 percent a year. The service helps people find Web sites, videos, products, people and other online information according to their tastes. Community members add more than 5 million recommendations per day, meaning StumbleUpon's depth improves the more often it is used. StumbleUpon combines peer recommendations with search features and as such presents an alternative to Web search leader Google Inc. . The recommendation features built into the service could serve as a referral system for eBay users to locate Web auctions that interest them, analysts say. eBay, based in San Jose, California, said it does not expect the StumbleUpon acquisition to have a material effect on its previously stated outlook for 2007 results. In April, the company had forecast full-year profit of $1.30 to $1.34 a share. (c) Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Republication or redistribution of Reuters content, including by caching, framing or simila