ing on the banking side as well. Last year, it bought Golden West Financial, one of the last major independent banks on the West Coast, in a $26 billion deal. Daniel J. Ludeman, currently president and chief executive of Wachovia Securities, will keep those roles at the combined brokerage firm. A.G. Edwards&#8217;s chairman and chief executive, Robert Bagby, will be chairman of the enlarged brokerage firm. Go to Article from The Associated Press via The New York Times Â» Go to Press Release from Wachovia Â» 12 comments so far... Great for Chris Gammon Wachovia&#8217;s new partner â€” Posted by Vivian I Gammon Assuming Wachovia got the buyout numbers right, as a shareholder think this is a very smart acquisition. An A.G. Edwards&#8217; office caught my attention when I attended a GOP county meeting the other day in a prosperous very small town Iowa county seat. Aside from a couple of local banks, it&#8217;s the only real financial game in town. â€” Posted by MARK KLEIN, M.D. As an employee of A.G. it leaves me with many questions but as a shareholder I&#8217;m pleased! I kind of take pride in the A.G. Edwards name. I hope that this doesn&#8217;t bring down the reputation the company has built up. â€” Posted by Tina Wachovia has a brilliant long term strategy. Little by little, step by step, year by year, they are setting the stage to becoming a true national bank, instead of just regional (East coast plus Texas and Calif.) They wait for the right time and the right price and they pounce. It may take another 10 years, but this is one well run and smart company. Kudos&#8230; â€” Posted by Ted Koppel Not in agreement here. Looking closely there are only the optics of a strategy that would truly work in the 1980&#8217;s but not going forward. It embraces size but not necessarily change much less agility. Wacovia management tends to say yes to many projects and investments without close, intelligent internal scrutiny. Too much Carolina Pride and not enough questioning and