http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-3&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/News/article/219792&cid=1116567986&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ TheStar.com - Business - Prosecution rests in Black case Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - Business - Prosecution rests in Black case Prosecution rests in Black case CHARLES REX ARBOGAST/AP PHOTO Conrad Black, 62, arrives at federal court in Chicago, May 30, 2007. The former media mogul is not expected to be called to the stand by defence lawyers. 2002 Black memo (.pdf) CP Video: Radler testimony, day 2 CP Video: Radler's first day Photos: Camera hits Amiel Black: In his own words Trial exhibits (DOJ site) Photos: Setting the scene A Conrad Black timeline Text of U.S. indictment (.pdf) Graphic: The trial (Flash) Video: Boxes episode, caught on tape Crime sheet: Lawyer's black trial blog Defence expected to take only one or two weeks, so verdict could be returned by the end of June May 31, 2007 04:30 AM CHICAGOâ€“After 43 days of testimony from 27 witnesses, prosecutors rested their case at the criminal trial of Conrad Black. Defence lawyers will take over today and Black's longtime executive assistant Joan Maida is expected to be the first witness. In a somewhat surprising twist after 11 weeks of prosecution witnesses, defence lawyers said yesterday that they would take just a week or two to present their evidence before the jury could begin deliberations. That could mean a verdict returned by the end of June. Black's lawyer Ed Genson said that he would take a little more than a full day to question all of the witnesses appearing on behalf of the besieged press baron. Black is not expected to be called to the stand. Also yesterday, prosecutors agreed to drop a count of money laundering against Black, but wouldn't elaborate on the reasons behind the decision. Gusts of chilly winter winds still blew through the downtown streets of Chicago when prosecutors opened their case against Black and three other Hollinger executives. "It was theft, it was fraud, it was crime," assistant U.S. attorney Jeffrey Cramer said in his opening statement. "Bank robbers wear masks and use a gun." Pointing to the Black and his co-defendants, Cramer remarked, "They dressed in ties and wore a suit." Since then, Cramer and other prosecution lawyers have guided a sometimes riveted, often snoozing, jury through a complicated thicket of details about the newspaper industry and non-compete agreements. Millions of dollars worth of non-compete payments, which prosecutors allege were misappropriated and should have remained with Hollinger International, form the crux of the government's case. In one agreement, Hollinger sold newspapers to a private company called Horizon that was controlled by Black and David Radler, the government's star witness who pleaded guilty and testified against Black. In the Horizon deal, Hollinger paid $1.2 million (U.S.) worth of non-competes to a closely held company that was also controlled by Black. "Black and Radler effectively paid themselves not to compete against themselves," assistant U.S. attorney Eric Sussman said during the trial. In at least one instance, Radler directed that non-compete money be paid to Black, himself and others even when he discovered that non-compete agreements did not exist. Prosecutors also plodded their way through details of Hollinger's juggernaut $3.5 billion (Canadian) sale of most of its Canadian newspapers to CanWest Global Communications Corp. in 2000. In that deal, the prosecution alleges that Black conspired to help co-defendants Peter Atkinson and Jack Boultbee receive non-compete money, even though CanWest had not asked that either sign such a pact. The prosecution also tried to show that Black has used company money to finance a lavish lifestyle for himself and his wife, Barbara Amiel. Prosecutors provided details of a $54,000 (U.S.) birthday party Black held for Amiel in 2000 at La Grenouille, a tony New York restaurant. When the bill for the party arrived, Black wrote to a colleague, "Let's call it one-third personal and two-thirds corporate." Radler, a self-described liar, testified that the dinner was solely a birthday celebration and that no businesses was conducted. Similarly, prosecutors spent several days questioning witnesses about a vacation Black and Amiel took in 2001 to Bora Bora. The cost of the trip was more than $500,000. Again, when the bill arrived, Black balked at paying. "No such outcome is acceptable," he wrote in an email that was introduced as evidence. Conrad Black on trial Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news Burlington soldier killed when helicopter shot down 'Don't let my son die in vain' A brother's quest for the truth moved mountains Report lays Ipperwash blame Nephew arrested in east-end slaying Lugovoi says British killed Litvinenko Record number of climbers conquer Everest Spain sues to recover sunken treasure 25 killed by Iraqi suicide bomber MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Horoscopes for Thursday, May 31 Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Stefani makes a clean getaway at the ACC Don Cherry takes his plaid to U.S. Crisp and buttery oatcakes Home of the million-dollar tuneup Ho Sang to receive the Gomez Award Woman bounced from Montreal gay bar Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
