http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-6&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DaieIMJ3.Xxjo%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116817306&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:15 , May 31 17:15 , Jun 01 01:15 Thomas H. Lee Agrees to Buy Ceridian for $5.3 Billion (Update3) By Ian King and Rochelle Garner May 30 (Bloomberg) -- Thomas H. Lee Partners LP and Fidelity National Financial Inc. agreed to buy Ceridian Corp. for $5.3 billion after shareholders pressed the company for changes. Ceridian investors will receive $36 a share, the companies said in a statement. That&#39;s 5.3 percent more than today&#39;s close and 17 percent higher than the price on Feb. 12, the day before the company said it would explore strategic options. The buyers may have been attracted to Ceridian&#39;s Comdata unit, which processes electronic payments and has outperformed the company&#39;s human resources services business. Pershing Square Capital Management LP, Ceridian&#39;s biggest shareholder, had called for a spinoff of the division since January to boost its value. ``Ceridian has leading market positions in large, growing markets,&#39;&#39; Fidelity National Financial Chief Executive Officer William P. Foley said in the statement. The Comdata unit provides private-label credit-cards to national trucking fleets that let drivers charge necessities including gasoline and motel rooms. Comdata also sells so-called ``stored value&#39;&#39; products such as Starbucks Corp. gift cards. Ceridian&#39;s slower-growing human resources unit offers payroll processing, tax filing and benefits administration. Customers including drugmaker GlaxoSmithKline Plc and chip- equipment company Teradyne Inc. use Ceridian to run programs such as employee wellness seminars. Ceridian shares gained 4.1 percent to $35.60 in extended trading after the announcement. They had advanced 47 cents to $34.19 at 4 p.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading and have added 22 percent this year. Pershing, a hedge fund founded by William Ackman, said on Jan. 18 it wanted Ceridian to spin off Comdata because its growth and cash flow have been diluted by other units that haven&#39;t performed as well. Ralph Whitworth&#39;s Relational Investors LLC joined the effort in February. The pressure led the Minneapolis-based company to hire financial and legal advisers to look at ways to boost its value. The company also has been fighting with Pershing over its May 14 firing of Gary Krow, who headed Ceridian&#39;s Comdata division, for disclosing confidential information to Pershing. Pershing said Krow&#39;s firing was part of a pattern by Ceridian of punishing whistleblowers. The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating how the company deals with internal ethics complaints as well as its accounting practices. Retailers and transportation companies have been snapping up Comdata&#39;s cards and services amid efforts to focus on electronic payments. Growth in human resources services hasn&#39;t kept up, though the business serves 25 million employees and 110,000 companies in 38 countries, and benefits from long-term orders. On May 1, the company said sales from human resources services would rise at a rate in the ``mid-single digits,&#39;&#39; while Comdata&#39;s growth would be in the ``low to mid-teens&#39;&#39; this year. Since 2002, Ceridian&#39;s sales have grown an average of 7 percent a year and totaled $1.6 billion in 2006. Net income jumped 36 percent last year to $173.6 million. Chief Executive Kathryn Marinello took over the top job in October last year after joining Ceridian from General Electric Co. where she was head of that GE Fleet Services Corp. She owns 162,790 shares Ceridian shares, according to an Oct. 20 filing. Buyout firms globally have engaged in 954 deals this year valued at $432.5 billion, according to Bloomberg data, following last year&#39;s record $701.5 billion. Thomas H. Lee and Fidelity expect to bring co-investors into the transaction, according to the statement. Fidelity will own less than 50 percent of Ceridian, which ended the first quarter with $92.1 million of debt and had $377.3 million in cash and equivalents, according to a May 1 statement. Ceridian plans to hold its annual shareholder meeting by Sept. 21 and said shareholders can vote on the deal then. The purchase is expected to close in the fourth quarter. Founded in 1974, Thomas H. Lee has invested $12 billion in more than 100 businesses. The firm manages now manages about $20 billion, according to the statement. Fidelity National Financial, which provides insurance and claims management services, issues about 29 percent of all title insurance policies in the U.S. Greenhill & Co. and law firm Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz advised Ceridian. Deutsche Bank Securities Inc. advised the buyout firms. Deutsche Bank and Credit Suisse are providing firm financing commitments to them, and Weil, Gotshal & Manges LLP is their legal adviser. To contact the reporter on this story: Ian King in San Francisco at ; Rochelle Garner in San Francisco at Last Updated: May 30, 2007 19:57 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Treasury 10-Year Yield at 2007 High on Chicago Business Index Increase
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-6&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/energy/2007-05-30-exxonmeeting_N.htm&cid=1116822769&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Exxon investors put exec pay above climate change - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Stock Market Answers: Ask Matt Test Drive: James R. Healey Managing Your Money Home Your Money: Sandra Block CD and Loan Rates Small Business Blog: Jim Hopkins Ask an Expert: Steve Strauss Entrepreneurial Tightrope: Gladys Edmunds Real solutions for your real estate needs. Choose from the selections below: Click here to begin Full service relocation assistance Apartments for rent in your area Need help financing or refinancing a home? Exxon investors put exec pay above climate change By Michael Erman and Ed Stoddard, Reuters spent much of its annual meeting Wednesday defending its environmental policy, but shareholders of the world's largest company were more concerned with executive pay and governance practices. In all, 15 shareholder proposals were up for approval at the annual meeting. Although none received 50% of the shareholder vote, four dealing with pay and governance received at least 40%. All four measures would increase the accountability of Exxon's management and board for their policies and performance. About 47.8% of the shareholders backed a measure that would give holders of 10% of Exxon's outstanding common shares the right to call special shareholder meetings and 47.2% favored a proposal to allow the company to recoup incentive bonuses it determined were unjustified. Proposals to give shareholders an advisory vote on executive pay and to split the chief executive and chairman positions got 41.2% and 40% of the vote, respectively. But climate change was the central topic of discussion at the meeting and one environmental proposal &#8212; that the company adopt goals for greenhouse gas reductions from its products and operations &#8212; received 31% of the shareholder vote. Exxon Chief Executive Rex Tillerson disputed claims by investor activists and environmentalists that the company is working to mislead the public about the causes of climate change. "What I find perplexing is why people feel threatened because we want to have a discussion," Tillerson said when offering an explanation for why the company funds some groups that are skeptical of the mainstream scientific views of climate change. "I'm not going to just adopt a slogan. If that makes me public enemy No. 1, so be it," he said. About three dozen protesters &#8212; outnumbered by police &#8212; staged a peaceful demonstration outside the meeting against the company's funding of groups they believe deny or distort the science of global warming. The protesters waved banners with slogans like "People Before Profits" and chanted "No More Junk Science." "ExxonMobil is double-crossing the public and policymakers. It's avoiding real changes and continuing to fund groups that purposefully distort the science of global warming," said Shawnee Hoover, the campaign director of Exxpose Exxon, a coalition of green and scientific groups. They say the company still funds about 40 organizations that the environmental group classified as "global warming deniers," shelling out more than $2 million to the groups in 2006. Exxon disagrees with the claim that the groups, many of which concern themselves with a wide range of issues, are "deniers of climate change." Scientists believe the use of fossil fuels causes global warming. Copyright 2007 Reuters Limited. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
