Nazem in 2003, 2005 and 2006 would fully vest when he steps down. His right to exercise those options along with some granted in 1999 will extend for three years and depend on his compliance, including an agreement not to engage in "certain competitive activities" for three years. Nazem's departure comes at a time, when Yahoo is banking on Panama - its new marketing platform to distribute ads - to work its magic on the company's revenues in the current and upcoming quarters. Yahoo posted an 11% drop in first quarter profits. Yahoo's Chief Technology Officer Parts Ways With Company [YHOO] 5/31/2007 2:38:56 AM Yahoo! Inc.'s (YHOO) chief technology officer Farzad Farzad Nazem is parting ways with the company after nearly a decade on the job. The resignation is effective June 8. The high-profile exit will leave two key posts empty at Yahoo, which streamlined operations into three core units last year to compete more effectively with Google and Microsoft. Nazem joined Yahoo in 1996, and became chief technology officer in 1998. Last year, Nazem was appointed to head the company's newly created technology group as part of a management shake up. Sue Decker, then CFO, was named to lead the advertiser & publisher group, while Yahoo is still on the hunt for a good candidate to lead its Audience group that includes consumer services like Yahoo News. Yahoo co-founder Jerry Yang will act as interim executive sponsor of the technology group until a successor is named. In a regulatory filing, Yahoo said it would pay Nazem a lump sum payment equal to his base salary for the period from June 8 through December 31, 2007. The stock options granted to Nazem in 2003, 2005 and 2006 would fully vest when he steps down. His right to exercise those options along with some granted in 1999 will extend for three years and depend on his compliance, including an agreement not to engage in "certain competitive activities" for three years. Nazem's departure comes at a time, when Yahoo is banking on