of Toledo, Ohio. The FDA said Tembec had added melamine, an agent used in plastics and fire retardants but unfit for use in food, to animal feed agents to improve the product's texture. The FDA said Tembec is a contract manufacturer for another company, Uniscope Inc. of Johnstown, Colo. The FDA said that small amounts of melamine detected in the feed products suggest that the "consumption of pork, chicken, domestic fish and eggs from animals inadvertently fed animal feed contaminated with melamine and its analogues is very unlikely to pose a human health risk." China Refuses Shipment of Evian But the agency said the products made by Tembec and Uniscope also reportedly contained "a urea formaldehyde resin-type ingredient," a raw ingredient used to make the binding agent in these products. The FDA says it is investigating that as well. The findings are likely to have a significant impact because in recent months world-wide alarm over the appearance of melamine in pet food and animal feed has centered on China. Beijing has borne the brunt of global criticism over laxity in supervising its food producers. In late March, the FDA identified a small Chinese manufacturer in Jiangsu province as the source of melamine in wheat flour shipped to the U.S. The chemical was detected in pet food ingredients and linked to a number of deaths in cats and dogs in the U.S., leading to a massive product recall. The FDA yesterday added that "the companies have confirmed that Tembec added melamine as part of the formulation of the products to improve the binding properties of pelleted feed. Melamine is not approved as an additive" for any food, including animal feed. The companies have stopped adding melamine to their products, the FDA said. Tembec BTLSR is a subsidiary of Tembec Inc., a forest products company based in Montreal, Canada, which manufacturers newsprint and chemicals, among other products. Tembec Inc., whose shares are listed on the Toronto stock exchange, reported annual sales of 3.3 billion Canadian dollars in 2006 and a net loss of C$304 million for 2005 and 2006. The company employs around 9,000 people. In its 2006 annual report, Tembec Inc. said that one of its manufacturing facilities located in Toledo, Ohio, manufactures melamine. A man who answered the phone at the office of Tembec BTLSR declined to comment on the FDA report, referring questions to John Valley, an official of the company. A message left for Mr. Valley late Wednesday night in Ohio wasn't immediately returned. Messages left late Wednesday night for officials in the public affairs division of Tembec Inc. also weren't immediately returned. There was no answer at Uniscope's office in Colorado late Wednesday night.
