http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.star-telegram.com/business/story/120572.html&cid=1116822769&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Star-Telegram.com | 05/31/2007 | Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent and all of North Texas Find Sales & Deals DFW Find a Home The Flower Mound Messenger DFW Find a Home Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent New executive counters criticism with charm and patience Exxon Mobil chief cools global-warming dissent DALLAS -- Global warming was a hot topic at the Exxon Mobil Corp. annual meeting Wednesday, but Chief Executive Rex Tillerson continued his effort to cool some of the criticisms of the oil-industry giant. Tillerson, continuing the conciliatory approach he undertook a year ago upon succeeding the combative Lee Raymond, patiently tried to convince environmental and social activists that Exxon Mobil is concerned about and is taking steps to address the possibility that human and industrial activity are causing global temperatures to rise. "We don't have a difference of views that it's an important issue," Tillerson said. "We have differences about what we know and what we don't know." A sizable group of activists critical of the company's environmental policies were among the 1,000 or so shareholders who turned out for the three-hour meeting at the Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center in downtown Dallas. One after another, critics took the microphone to criticize Exxon Mobil's past policies and support of groups that question the validity and the science behind the claims that global warming is largely caused by human consumption of fossil fuels. Framing their arguments in management terms, activists charged that Exxon Mobil's efforts have hurt the company's image and threatened to undermine its long-term financial viability. Andrew Logan of the Investor Network on Climate Risk pointedly asked why Exxon Mobil "has put so much effort into making itself public enemy Number 1 in terms of the global-warming debate" by openly opposing calls for the U.S. and foreign governments to make significant environmental policy changes. "You've sacrificed the company's reputation by taking a position that, it seems to me, is to the benefit of no one," Logan said. Tillerson, as he did repeatedly throughout the meeting, responded in measured tones. "We never set out to make the company public enemy Number 1," Tillerson said. Exxon's differences with global-warming activists, he said, have always been over the degree of certainty involved in the science of climate change. "What I find perplexing," Tillerson said, "is why people feel so threatened because we want to have a discussion" about the scientific issues "and what is known and what is not known." Even under Raymond, Tillerson said, Exxon Mobil has sought to support organizations that back work on the science of global warming and cutting carbon-dioxide emissions. Company scientists and engineers have played a role in the efforts of the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, which has authored leading studies on climate change. Other critics, saying Exxon Mobil should seek to be a broad-based energy company, called for it to take a more active role and devote a share of its research and development funds and expertise in the development of alternative fuels rather than continue investing almost entirely in oil and gas production. "We do not oppose the development of alternatives to fossil fuels," Tillerson said, attempting to cool the discussion. But Exxon Mobil's expertise has made it the industry leader in oil and gas production and, Tillerson said, estimates of the world's rising energy requirements for the next 25 years show that the majority will still come from fossil fuels such as oil, natural gas and coal. Tillerson's charm offensive may not be winning many converts among the ranks of environmental and social activists, but it may be lessening the tension somewhat. None of the 15 shareholder proposals, all opposed by management, was approved. But several gained more than 40 percent of the votes cast, a significant advance against the management opposition. A year ago, for the first time in memory, a management-opposed measure was approved. One of the rejected proposals called for the company to adopt specific goals for reducing its own carbon-dioxide emissions to help counter global warming. It received a 31 percent favorable vote. The proposal gaining the most support, 47.8 percent, would have amended the company's bylaws to allow shareholders representing 10 percent of the company's stock to call a special shareholders meeting. The com- pany said such a provision now exists, provided shareholders can show good cause in court to call such a meeting. Tillerson, at the conclusion of the meeting, extended an olive branch to the dissidents among the Exxon Mobil shareholders. "I really do appreciate all of your comments today and the respectful way they were presented." DIRECTORS AND SHAREHOLDER INITIATIVES Shareholders overwhelmingly approved the election of all Exxon Mobil's nominated directors. Economist Michael Boskin of the free-market oriented Hoover Institution at Stanford University received the least support, 93 percent of the vote. New director Steve Reinemund, former chairman and CEO of PepsiCo, received a 98 percent favorable vote. 7.8 percent favored a proposal to allow shareholders representing 10 percent of the company's stock to call a special shareholders meeting. The company said such a provision now exists, provided shareholders can show good cause in court. 7.2 percent supported a resolution asking the Exxon Mobil board to adopt a bylaw allowing the company to recoup unearned bonuses or other incentive payments to senior executives. 1.2 percent voted for a proposal that would have allowed shareholders to vote on an advisory resolution approving the pay and other compensation of senior company executives. 1 percent voted for the company to adopt specific goals for reducing its own carbon-dioxide emissions to help counter global warming. About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/05/31/business/motorola.1-65313.php&cid=1116823896&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Motorola plans to cut 4,000 more jobs - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Motorola plans to cut 4,000 more jobs Published: May 31, 2007 The latest round of cuts means the world&#039;s No.2 handset maker has announced plans to eliminate more than 10 percent of its workforce since the start of 2007 to improve sagging financial and operational results. The cellphone maker Motorola said it would cut another 4,000 jobs as part of a plan to improve sagging financial and operational results. The latest round of cuts means Motorola, the world&#039;s No. 2 handset maker, has announced plans to eliminate more than 10 percent of its work force since the start of 2007, when it became clear that two years of strong momentum behind its popular Razr phone had collapsed. The company is already eliminating 3,500 jobs as part of a two-year cost-cutting plan to save $400 million. Those layoffs, announced in January, are to be completed by June 30. Motorola said Wednesday that it would save another $600 million in 2008 by cutting 4,000 more workers, prioritizing investments and putting controls on discretionary spending and general and administrative expenses. US economy grows by just 0.6 percent in the first quarter Wachovia buys A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion . Deutsche Telekom executive who once worked at Siemens to leave company The company did not specify where the new cuts would be made. A spokeswoman, Jennifer Weyrauch, said they would be achieved through a mixture of attrition and layoffs. The company expects to take a restructuring charge of $300 million, or 8 cents per share, in 2007, from severance and related expenses from staff cuts. Tom Meredith, Motorola&#039;s chief financial executive, said the move was an "update to the commitment" the company had made "to drive out additional costs, and a continuation of the plan we announced in January." Motorola&#039;s work force, which stood at 150,000 people worldwide as recently as 2000, had declined to 66,000 at the beginning of the year. Weyrauch said the company, which has acquired several smaller firms in recent months, also is continuing to hire. It remains to be seen whether it can come up with a hit successor to the Razr, the success of which has been eroded by declining sale prices and competitors&#039; new phones. Wall Street appeared to modestly approve of the latest cuts. Motorola shares rose 12 cents in extended-hours trading after closing the regular session down 2 cents at $18.28. "From a cost-cutting perspective, these are steps in the right direction for the long term," said John Slack, a Morningstar analyst. "But the big issue to underscore is that products in the market are the key, and that is a slow ship to turn." Motorola began to cut back in January in an effort to recover from a series of miscues that caused it to lose about a third of its market value since October. It had ridden the Razr to significant gains in the world cellphone market for two years, closing the gap on its rival Nokia. But its strategy of cutting prices sharply to sell more units backfired, hammering its profit margins. Exacerbating its troubles, Ron Garriques departed abruptly in February as head of the cellphone unit. This spring, the company posted its first quarterly loss since 2004 and executives indicated that its efforts had not gone far enough. Motorola has already warned that its results from the April-June quarter will not be good. French presidency gets a bold new style Man with rare tuberculosis tells his tale Naples&#39;s trash is a challenge politicians are flunking Jihadist groups fill a Palestinian power vacuum Russia worried over UN plans for Kosovo independence Ernst & Young Won&#39;t Face Criminal Charges Thai court orders dis