http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-0&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3DahNZsWtauvTk%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116844899&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ , May 31 12:17 , May 31 17:17 , Jun 01 01:17 Treasury 10-Year Yield at 9-Month High as Business Index Jumps By Elizabeth Stanton and Deborah Finestone May 31 (Bloomberg) -- U.S. Treasuries fell, pushing the benchmark 10-year note&#39;s yield to its highest level since August, after a measure of business activity rose more than forecast. Expectations the Federal Reserve will cut interest rates this year fell to the lowest since last July as the National Association for Purchasing Management-Chicago report indicated the economy is rebounding from a first-quarter slowdown. U.S. equities extended an advance that yesterday pushed the Standard & Poor&#39;s 500 Index to a record. ``I wouldn&#39;t be surprised to see people change their minds and raise the probability of the Fed hiking,&#39;&#39; said Ajay Rajadhyaksha, co-head of U.S. fixed-income strategy in New York at Barclays Capital, one of the 21 primary dealers that underwrite the U.S. government&#39;s debt. ``Yields will continue to move higher.&#39;&#39; The 10-year note&#39;s yield, which moves inversely to its price, rose more than 3 basis points, or 0.03 percentage point, to 4.9022 percent at 11:33 a.m. in New York, according to bond broker Cantor Fitzgerald LP. Earlier it touched 4.917 percent, the highest since Aug. 16. Until today, the highest level of the year was 4.902 percent on Jan. 26. The price of 4 1/2 percent notes maturing in May 2017 fell 9/32, or $2.81 per $1,000 face amount, to 96 27/32. The Dow Jones Industrial Average also rose from a record, and the Morgan Stanley Capital International Emerging Markets Index increased the most since March, approaching its May 22 record. ``Overlap the S&P and the 10-year contract, and you&#39;d see a very good correlation,&#39;&#39; said Jeffry Feigenwinter, head of U.S. Treasury trading at primary dealer BNP Paribas Securities Corp. in New York. ``Everybody thinks the market&#39;s cheap, but it&#39;s really still expensive&#39;&#39; relative to the overnight lending rate set by the Fed. The NAPM-Chicago&#39;s business barometer rose to 61.7 in May from 52.9 in April. Readings greater than 50 signal expansion. The median forecast of economists polled by Bloomberg was for a smaller increase to 54.0. ``We&#39;ll have to see if this follows through with the ISM number tomorrow,&#39;&#39; said Theodore Ake, head of U.S. government bond trading in New York at primary dealer Mizuho Securities USA Inc. He referred to the Institute for Supply Management&#39;s manufacturing index. The median forecast was for a decline to 54.0 from 54.7 in April. On a comparable increase in that gauge, ``the market&#39;s going to have to take out the fact that the next move from the Fed is an ease, and that any kind of ease in 2007 is out of the question,&#39;&#39; Ake said. Yields on Eurodollar futures expiring in December rose to the highest since July as traders pared bets on interest-rate cuts by the Fed. The yields forecast the interest rate on three- month bank deposits, which closely tracks the Fed&#39;s target for the overnight lending rate between banks. The three-month deposit rate, also known as Libor, is 5.36 percent. The federal funds target is 5.25 percent. The December Eurodollar futures yield rose 3 basis points to 5.285 percent, the highest since July 25. The market had little reaction to a government report showing the U.S. economy in the first quarter expanded at a slower pace than originally estimated. Gross domestic product grew at a rate of 0.6 percent, compared with an initial estimate of 1.3 percent, the Commerce Department said. The median forecast of economists polled by Bloomberg was for a revision to 0.8 percent. While the pace of GDP growth was the weakest in more than four years, reports have shown that business spending has improved in the second quarter. Minutes of Fed policy makers&#39; most recent meeting, released yesterday, showed they still expect growth to accelerate this year and are primarily concerned about inflation. A Labor Department report released at the same time as the GDP report showed new claims for state unemployment insurance benefits last week fell below their average for all of last year, pointing to strength in the labor market. The department&#39;s monthly employment report for May is forecast to show job creation accelerated. First-time claims for state jobless benefits fell to 310,000 for the week ended May 26, from a revised 314,000 during the prior period. Last year&#39;s average was 313,000. Treasuries may benefit later today from the monthly rebalancing of bond indexes to include securities issued during the month. Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc., whose U.S. investment-grade bond indexes are used as benchmarks by managers of $2.5 trillion, estimated the duration of its U.S. Treasury Index will increase by 0.22 years when the index is rebalanced, the most since August 2002. Duration measures price sensitivity to changes in yield, and is partly a function of maturity. Some portfolio managers buy bonds around the time of a rebalancing that causes the index&#39;s duration to lengthen. The so- called index extensions in February, May, August and November are larger than in other months because 10-year notes and 30-year bonds are sold then. Lehman&#39;s indexes are rebalanced at 3 p.m. New York time on the last business day of the month. Bonds issued during the month move into the index, and ones that no longer fit the index criteria are removed. The duration of the Treasury index was 4.77 years yesterday. To contact the reporters for this story: Elizabeth Stanton in New York at ; Deborah Finestone in New York at Last Updated: May 31, 2007 11:36 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division U.S. Economy Grows at 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Home Prices in U.S. Climbed at Slowest Pace in Decade During First Quarter
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/business/317825_jeppesen31.html&cid=1116798859&ei=muxeRt2jO5CUrgOCrPHUDQ Jeppesen provides added aviation services Skip ads and navigation Last updated May 30, 2007 10:12 p.m. PT Jeppesen provides added aviation services Jeppesen Dataplan Inc., sued by the American Civil Liberties Union on Wednesday, is a subsidiary of Boeing Commercial Aviation Services, which is a unit of Boeing Commercial Airplanes. Based in Englewood, Colo., Jeppesen is the world's largest provider of flight information services, such as the navigation charts that pilots use. It produces more than 2 billion such charts a year. The Boeing Co. acquired Jeppesen in August 2000 as part of its strategy to expand in the aviation services business, which Boeing estimated at the time would generate more than $2.6 trillion over the next two decades. The $1.5 billion in cash Boeing paid for the company was about six times Jeppesen's 1999 revenue of $235 million. Boeing has continued to grow Jeppesen, but it does not break out that revenue separately from overall sales in commercial airplanes. In its bid to acquire Jeppesen from the Tribune Co., Boeing had to beat out 10 other competitors. The media giant shed Jeppesen to help pay off debt after its purchase of the Los Angeles Times. When Boeing acquired Jeppesen, then-Boeing Chairman and Chief Executive Phil Condit had this to say: "This really is the glue to providing a whole set of information services. In the long run, we are trying to buy a business that can continue to grow." Jeppesen has since provided Boeing with an important and consistent revenue stream, according to industry analysts, although the amount is probably tiny compared with the more than $40 billion in annual sales generated by Boeing's jetliner business. P-I aerospace reporter James Wallace can be reached at 206-448-8040 or . Read his Aerospace blog at What do you think? Add P-I Business headlines t